    {
      "turn_number": 40,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Okay — there's so much that keeps bubbling up. I lie awake thinking about worst-case scenarios and then shame myself for thinking them, like I should be grateful to be pregnant at all. Driving past the Smith College campus still makes my hands clamp the wheel because every clinic visit feels like a reminder that anything could go wrong. I want someone to say plainly, \"We hear you. We'll watch you closely and we'll call you if anything changes,\" instead of a parade of different midwives reciting test results like they're reading from a script.\n\nI worry about money — gas, missed work, who takes the kids when I’m in the hospital. That practical anxiety mixes with the medical fear until I’m exhausted. Small gestures matter: a nurse who sits down, explains things in plain words, asks about my other kids, offers a warm blanket. That makes me feel like a person, not a problem. Mostly I want to come out the other side holding my baby and my life still intact — and for someone to acknowledge that’s what I'm fighting for.",
      "responding_to_question_id": "Q19",
      "input_tokens": 1592,
      "output_tokens": 411
    },
